To execute Python code from JavaScript in JupyterLab, you must create a plugin that accesses the kernel via the JupyterLab application instance. Here’s a basic example:

typescript
import { JupyterLab, JupyterLabPlugin } from '@jupyterlab/application';
import { Kernel } from '@jupyterlab/services';

const extension: JupyterLabPlugin<void> = {
  id: 'your-extension-id',
  requires: [Kernel.IKernelConnection],
  activate: (app: JupyterLab, kernel: Kernel.IKernelConnection) => {
    kernel.execute('x = 42'); // Execute Python code directly
  }
};

export default extension;


This requires the `Kernel.IKernelConnection` service to access the kernel and execute Python code.

To access the kernel in a JupyterLab plugin, you must declare a dependency on `Kernel.IKernelConnection` in the `requires` array of your plugin. This injects a live kernel connection into your plugin's `activate` function, allowing you to call `kernel.execute()` or other kernel-related methods. Example:

typescript
requires: [Kernel.IKernelConnection],
activate: (app: JupyterLab, kernel: Kernel.IKernelConnection) => {
  kernel.execute('print("Hello from Python")');
}

To print the result of a Python expression, use the kernel's `requestExecute` method and listen for `iopub` messages. Here’s an example:

typescript
import { JupyterLab, JupyterLabPlugin } from '@jupyterlab/application';
import { Kernel } from '@jupyterlab/services';

const extension: JupyterLabPlugin<void> = {
  id: 'execute-and-print',
  requires: [Kernel.IKernelConnection],
  activate: (app: JupyterLab, kernel: Kernel.IKernelConnection) => {
    kernel.requestExecute({ code: 'x = 42' }).onIOPub = (msg) => {
      if (msg.header.msg_type === 'stream' && msg.content.text) {
        console.log('Result:', msg.content.text);
      }
    };
  }
};

export default extension;


This executes `x = 42` and logs any output streamed back from the kernel.
